00:05:49.202 --> 00:05:50.995
MIKE MARRINER: So everyone
always asks like, how did

00:05:50.995 --> 00:05:52.630
Roadtrip Nation start?

00:05:52.630 --> 00:05:53.640
Was it a business plan?

00:05:53.640 --> 00:05:55.870
Was it some kind of
post-doctoral thesis or

00:05:55.870 --> 00:05:56.560
something like that?

00:05:56.560 --> 00:05:58.800
But it it's actually
none of that.

00:05:58.800 --> 00:06:01.280
It was really just Nate, Brian,
and I being in school

00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:03.720
and wondering, what do we want
to do with our lives?

00:06:03.720 --> 00:06:06.210
And we started to realize
there's no class in school to

00:06:06.210 --> 00:06:08.335
help you figure out what do you
want to do with your life.

00:06:08.335 --> 00:06:09.780
We though that was kind of
funny, because there's all

00:06:09.780 --> 00:06:11.940
these classes for math and
English and science.

00:06:11.940 --> 00:06:13.530
Those are, obviously, really
important things.

00:06:13.530 --> 00:06:16.920
But we felt the big elephant in
the room was, well, what do

00:06:16.920 --> 00:06:18.090
you want to do with your life?

00:06:18.090 --> 00:06:20.110
And so when we asked our
teachers this, they said, go

00:06:20.110 --> 00:06:21.200
talk to your school counselor.

00:06:21.200 --> 00:06:23.310
Maybe they can help you figure
out what do you want to do

00:06:23.310 --> 00:06:24.130
with your life.

00:06:24.130 --> 00:06:25.580
And so we went to
our counselor.

00:06:25.580 --> 00:06:28.350
And the counselor told us, OK,
take, I think, it was the

00:06:28.350 --> 00:06:29.890
Myers-Briggs test or something
like that.

00:06:29.890 --> 00:06:31.480
You fill in some dots.

00:06:31.480 --> 00:06:34.270
And we were like, seriously?

00:06:34.270 --> 00:06:36.570
NATHAN GEBHARD: I was supposed
to be a plumber.

00:06:36.570 --> 00:06:37.520
That was the big finding.

00:06:37.520 --> 00:06:40.740
I should be a plumber.

00:06:40.740 --> 00:06:42.700
MIKE MARRINER: So, essentially,
at that point, we

00:06:42.700 --> 00:06:44.880
really felt, intuitively, that
we needed something more

00:06:44.880 --> 00:06:48.320
exploratory, something
more humanized.

00:06:48.320 --> 00:06:50.260
And so that's when
we had the idea.

00:06:50.260 --> 00:06:53.380
It wasn't as much to create
Roadtrip Nation, as it was,

00:06:53.380 --> 00:06:57.470
what if we could hit the road
and go talk to people who are

00:06:57.470 --> 00:07:00.100
doing interesting things, all
across America, and ask them,

00:07:00.100 --> 00:07:02.710
how did you get to where
you are today?

00:07:02.710 --> 00:07:04.770
NATHAN GEBHARD: I think it
really came in this real

00:07:04.770 --> 00:07:05.980
visceral sense.

00:07:05.980 --> 00:07:09.400
I remember being in college and
passing my resume out at a

00:07:09.400 --> 00:07:11.640
career fair.

00:07:11.640 --> 00:07:12.960
I was a business major.

00:07:12.960 --> 00:07:15.110
And so it was like a little
assembly line.

00:07:15.110 --> 00:07:18.550
Business majors at the school
I was at become consultants.

00:07:18.550 --> 00:07:21.320
And so I was passing my resume
out to like, Arthur Andersen,

00:07:21.320 --> 00:07:22.460
all these different companies.

00:07:22.460 --> 00:07:25.650
And I remember handing my resume
to a guy and saying

00:07:25.650 --> 00:07:29.980
like, I have no idea what you
do or what I'm applying for.

00:07:29.980 --> 00:07:31.640
What is this thing?

00:07:31.640 --> 00:07:33.450
And I remember taking him
out to lunch one day.

00:07:33.450 --> 00:07:37.690
And I was like, I just need to
see what this things about,

00:07:37.690 --> 00:07:38.900
that I'm applying for.

00:07:38.900 --> 00:07:40.150
And I remember getting
to lunch.

00:07:40.150 --> 00:07:41.750
And he had a suit and tie on.

00:07:41.750 --> 00:07:44.250
And I waited politely
for a while.

00:07:44.250 --> 00:07:47.810
And I was like, so do you have
to wear the suit all the time?

00:07:47.810 --> 00:07:49.130
And he was really fired
up about it.

00:07:49.130 --> 00:07:50.660
He was like, yeah, you
get to dress nice.

00:07:50.660 --> 00:07:52.400
They give you a budget
for clothes.

00:07:52.400 --> 00:07:57.290
And the blood just completely
drained out of my body.

00:07:57.290 --> 00:07:59.420
I could just instantly, in
that one simple moment,

00:07:59.420 --> 00:08:02.340
realize that this whole path
that I was put on, to make

00:08:02.340 --> 00:08:05.500
money and get that mortgage
and be a professional, was

00:08:05.500 --> 00:08:08.390
just kind of falling apart at
the simplest thing of like, I

00:08:08.390 --> 00:08:10.060
can't wear a suit every day.

00:08:10.060 --> 00:08:12.210
I think we, each of us, had that
freak out moment, where

00:08:12.210 --> 00:08:15.180
we really realized we needed to
see what else was out there

00:08:15.180 --> 00:08:17.870
and what we were
interested in.

00:08:17.870 --> 00:08:18.470
BRIAN MCALLISTER: And
I think so much of

00:08:18.470 --> 00:08:19.560
it was lack of exposure.

00:08:19.560 --> 00:08:21.710
Like to Nate's point, we
didn't really know

00:08:21.710 --> 00:08:22.460
what was out there.

00:08:22.460 --> 00:08:25.530
And to what Mike was saying,
you take these tests, these

00:08:25.530 --> 00:08:28.070
assessment tests, and Nate
figures out he's going to

00:08:28.070 --> 00:08:28.870
become a plumber.

00:08:28.870 --> 00:08:32.580
But we really needed something
more human.

00:08:32.580 --> 00:08:35.049
There was almost like a
frustration that, at the end

00:08:35.049 --> 00:08:36.890
of the day, we just wanted to go
out and talk to people from

00:08:36.890 --> 00:08:39.230
all walks of life and ask
them, how did you get

00:08:39.230 --> 00:08:40.039
to where you are?

00:08:40.039 --> 00:08:41.890
Was there ever a time in your
life that, perhaps, you're

00:08:41.890 --> 00:08:43.900
going through a period of
ambiguity, or you were

00:08:43.900 --> 00:08:46.430
displaced, or you just weren't
sure where the next step was?

00:08:46.430 --> 00:08:51.230
Or how did you identify those
values within and see that?

00:08:51.230 --> 00:08:54.420
And how did you align
a lifestyle or a

00:08:54.420 --> 00:08:55.670
culture to a job?

00:08:55.670 --> 00:08:57.320
And I think these were some
of the questions we were

00:08:57.320 --> 00:08:58.000
challenging with.

00:08:58.000 --> 00:09:01.610
And it wasn't like academia
was bringing this to us.

00:09:01.610 --> 00:09:03.960
As you guys know, a lot of cool
projects sometimes start

00:09:03.960 --> 00:09:04.960
in a garage.

00:09:04.960 --> 00:09:07.260
This project was started
out in a motor home.

00:09:07.260 --> 00:09:09.200
So we bought my parents old,
beat-up motor home.

00:09:09.200 --> 00:09:10.230
The thing barely ran.

00:09:10.230 --> 00:09:11.060
I mean, Nate and I--

00:09:11.060 --> 00:09:11.620
NATHAN GEBHARD: It
didn't matter.

00:09:11.620 --> 00:09:13.520
BRIAN MCALLISTER: We pretty
much fixed the thing as we

00:09:13.520 --> 00:09:16.680
travelled across the
United States.

00:09:16.680 --> 00:09:18.410
And this was our vehicle.

00:09:18.410 --> 00:09:23.070
This was our space.

00:09:23.070 --> 00:09:24.790
So this thing was an old,
beat-up motor home.

00:09:24.790 --> 00:09:26.760
We painted it green, because
the paint was on

00:09:26.760 --> 00:09:28.160
sale at Home Depot.

00:09:28.160 --> 00:09:30.040
I mean we were funding this
thing through credit cards.

00:09:30.040 --> 00:09:32.470
It wasn't like we had some agent
behind us that was like,

00:09:32.470 --> 00:09:35.430
hey, we're going to make you
guys some reality show on MTV.

00:09:35.430 --> 00:09:37.520
It was very, very sincere
and authentic.

00:09:37.520 --> 00:09:42.340
And we started just to question
like, who's out there

00:09:42.340 --> 00:09:43.390
doing creative things?

00:09:43.390 --> 00:09:45.140
Who's out there really
changing the world?

00:09:45.140 --> 00:09:46.480
Where are some of these
change agents?

00:09:46.480 --> 00:09:48.480
And let's ask them, like,
what's driving them?

00:09:48.480 --> 00:09:51.940
And so that's what led us to
the people that we actually

00:09:51.940 --> 00:09:52.980
ended up interviewing.

00:09:52.980 --> 00:09:54.350
We booked over 85 interviews.

00:09:54.350 --> 00:09:57.550
We got denied, probably,
500 times, 1,000 times.

00:09:57.550 --> 00:10:01.790
And we found these people
through magazine articles,

00:10:01.790 --> 00:10:04.580
different subscriptions that
we're applying, magazines.

00:10:04.580 --> 00:10:06.460
We were combing through
mastheads.

00:10:06.460 --> 00:10:09.190
We found ourselves at newspaper
stands just saying,

00:10:09.190 --> 00:10:10.320
where are the cool people?

00:10:10.320 --> 00:10:11.250
What are they doing?

00:10:11.250 --> 00:10:13.950
And let's go talk to them and
ask them, how did you get to

00:10:13.950 --> 00:10:15.230
where you are today?

00:10:15.230 --> 00:10:18.250
NATHAN GEBHARD: And it was this
simple sense of I like

00:10:18.250 --> 00:10:20.380
snowboarding, and I like art.

00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:23.530
Well, what about the guys that
put that together, like the

00:10:23.530 --> 00:10:24.620
art on snowboards?

00:10:24.620 --> 00:10:27.690
And so like literally just cold
called Burton Snowboards

00:10:27.690 --> 00:10:30.680
and said like can we talk
to somebody there?

00:10:30.680 --> 00:10:33.400
I'm kind of a tech geek.

00:10:33.400 --> 00:10:35.750
I was watching TV, and there
was a Dell commercial.

00:10:35.750 --> 00:10:37.790
And I got the 1-800
number off the

00:10:37.790 --> 00:10:39.250
commercial to buy a computer.

00:10:39.250 --> 00:10:42.770
And I just asked for Michael,
Michael Dell.

00:10:42.770 --> 00:10:45.870
And it was about six transfers
later, and I ended up speaking

00:10:45.870 --> 00:10:47.530
to Laura Strange, who was
