BRIAN MCALLISTER: So it was
such a transformative

00:24:21.810 --> 00:24:24.220
experience on the three of us
that we really came back from

00:24:24.220 --> 00:24:27.850
this three and a half month
journey having a drive and a

00:24:27.850 --> 00:24:28.740
desire to share.

00:24:28.740 --> 00:24:32.000
We had a lot of friends that we
felt needed to hear some of

00:24:32.000 --> 00:24:36.720
these stories and break down
some of their master plans or

00:24:36.720 --> 00:24:38.000
even just provide perspective.

00:24:38.000 --> 00:24:39.520
I think that was probably one
of the biggest things that I

00:24:39.520 --> 00:24:41.956
took away, from being on this
journey, was just perspective

00:24:41.956 --> 00:24:47.330
of identifying who you are
and how to align it.

00:24:47.330 --> 00:24:47.740
You guys heard--

00:24:47.740 --> 00:24:49.880
Jager's actually one most
influential interviews that we

00:24:49.880 --> 00:24:53.290
had on that trip, as he just
talked about distinction.

00:24:53.290 --> 00:24:54.405
And you've got to wear it on
your shoulder, and you've got

00:24:54.405 --> 00:24:55.510
to be proud about it.

00:24:55.510 --> 00:24:57.960
And I think we had the fear
of having this milquetoast

00:24:57.960 --> 00:24:59.630
existence, that you
get washed around.

00:24:59.630 --> 00:25:02.080
And I think like, coming back
from that journey was really

00:25:02.080 --> 00:25:03.600
something that the three
of us went through.

00:25:03.600 --> 00:25:07.320
But it was more of a
desire to share it.

00:25:07.320 --> 00:25:09.440
What we wanted to share with
you guys is that original

00:25:09.440 --> 00:25:12.160
trip, because it's rooted in
everything that we do now.

00:25:12.160 --> 00:25:15.850
It really provided
the framework of

00:25:15.850 --> 00:25:17.510
where we are today.

00:25:17.510 --> 00:25:21.220
But it was definitely a long,
long journey of how we got

00:25:21.220 --> 00:25:22.730
from that original road trip,
in an old, beat-up

00:25:22.730 --> 00:25:24.680
motor home, to today.

00:25:24.680 --> 00:25:26.320
MIKE MARRINER: So everyone
always asks that question.

00:25:26.320 --> 00:25:29.310
We know you took Brian's old,
family RV, painted it green

00:25:29.310 --> 00:25:30.230
and lived in it for
three months and

00:25:30.230 --> 00:25:30.730
did that whole thing.

00:25:30.730 --> 00:25:34.980
But how do it evolve into this
organization that has an

00:25:34.980 --> 00:25:37.130
annual documentary series and
a nonprofit education

00:25:37.130 --> 00:25:40.050
foundation that has curriculum
in schools across America and

00:25:40.050 --> 00:25:41.790
all that stuff?

00:25:41.790 --> 00:25:45.890
And think there's no
real clean answer.

00:25:45.890 --> 00:25:47.950
I think the best way we can
describe is there was a very

00:25:47.950 --> 00:25:51.110
incremental, evolutionary
process over a 10 year period.

00:25:51.110 --> 00:25:54.280
And that we didn't go out and
get venture capital and scale

00:25:54.280 --> 00:25:55.000
it over two years.

00:25:55.000 --> 00:25:57.440
I mean it's something that we
did very incrementally and in

00:25:57.440 --> 00:26:01.210
as organic and mission-based
a manner as we could.

00:26:01.210 --> 00:26:04.670
And it really started with, on
that road trip, we had met

00:26:04.670 --> 00:26:06.180
someone who was a writer
at "Forbes

00:26:06.180 --> 00:26:08.050
Magazine," in New York City.

00:26:08.050 --> 00:26:10.470
And she tagged along for some of
those interviews we did in

00:26:10.470 --> 00:26:12.760
New York City, like Len Riggio,
from Barnes &amp; Noble,

00:26:12.760 --> 00:26:15.170
and "Saturday Night Live." and
she ended up doing a very

00:26:15.170 --> 00:26:17.280
small article in "Forbes"
on Roadtrip Nation.

00:26:17.280 --> 00:26:18.920
It was definitely not
a cover story.

00:26:18.920 --> 00:26:20.940
It was literally two inches.

00:26:20.940 --> 00:26:22.370
But it got a little
bit of attention.

00:26:22.370 --> 00:26:24.740
And we learned that big New York
book publishers, if you

00:26:24.740 --> 00:26:27.540
get an article in a magazine
like that, there's some

00:26:27.540 --> 00:26:28.460
credibility.

00:26:28.460 --> 00:26:30.590
So through a series of events,
we ended up getting a

00:26:30.590 --> 00:26:34.290
publishing contract with
Random House's imprint

00:26:34.290 --> 00:26:35.140
Ballantine Books.

00:26:35.140 --> 00:26:36.670
And that's the book that's
in the back there.

00:26:36.670 --> 00:26:38.520
But essentially, we had the
chance, for a year and a half

00:26:38.520 --> 00:26:41.740
after that road trip, to write
a book about our experiences,

00:26:41.740 --> 00:26:44.075
really reflect on some of the
content and the stories and

00:26:44.075 --> 00:26:46.830
the insights we gained over
that experience and

00:26:46.830 --> 00:26:48.160
release that book.

00:26:48.160 --> 00:26:50.330
The book came out in 2003.

00:26:50.330 --> 00:26:51.630
It didn't sell very
well at first.

00:26:51.630 --> 00:26:53.960
It was like the 600,000th best
selling book in America.

00:26:53.960 --> 00:26:56.020
And we were like, no big deal.

00:26:56.020 --> 00:26:57.400
We had a great experience.

00:26:57.400 --> 00:27:00.960
And then the publisher got
behind it and put us on this

00:27:00.960 --> 00:27:02.820
major PR blitz.

00:27:02.820 --> 00:27:07.590
And we were on CNN, "Carson Daly
Show," "Newsweek," NPR,

00:27:07.590 --> 00:27:10.285
"Today Show." And the day we
were on the "Today Show", it

00:27:10.285 --> 00:27:13.420
became 15th best selling book
in America on Amazon.

00:27:13.420 --> 00:27:14.320
It was just for a day.

00:27:14.320 --> 00:27:17.100
But we still claim it.

00:27:17.100 --> 00:27:19.850
Mom and dad are proud.

00:27:19.850 --> 00:27:22.910
But around that time, there was
lots of different kind of

00:27:22.910 --> 00:27:27.710
energy for Roadtrip Nation,
Hollywood agents and MTV show

00:27:27.710 --> 00:27:29.130
this, and blah, blah, blah.

00:27:29.130 --> 00:27:31.170
And around that time, that's
when we really got intentional

00:27:31.170 --> 00:27:33.360
with building a grassroots
organization that was

00:27:33.360 --> 00:27:36.130
mission-based that could empower
other people to define

00:27:36.130 --> 00:27:37.520
their own roads in life.

00:27:37.520 --> 00:27:39.750
And one of the first steps that
we took was too launch a

00:27:39.750 --> 00:27:43.220
series on public television by
first creating a program, on

00:27:43.220 --> 00:27:45.450
college campuses, called "Behind
the Wheel," where

00:27:45.450 --> 00:27:47.950
college students could apply for
the chance to go on these

00:27:47.950 --> 00:27:49.440
annual summer road trips.

00:27:49.440 --> 00:27:52.420
We had a few organizations that
got behind us to support

00:27:52.420 --> 00:27:54.430
it and fund the production.

00:27:54.430 --> 00:27:58.310
And over a period of 7 years,
we expanded to 350 college

00:27:58.310 --> 00:27:59.860
campuses across America.

00:27:59.860 --> 00:28:02.390
We created a fleet
of motor homes.

00:28:02.390 --> 00:28:04.330
These trips went around
the world to

00:28:04.330 --> 00:28:06.070
New Zealand, Australia.

00:28:06.070 --> 00:28:09.380
There was Roadtrip Nation Israel
in Hebrew, Africa,

00:28:09.380 --> 00:28:11.670
South America, all over.

00:28:11.670 --> 00:28:14.500
And the movement proliferated
on a college level.

00:28:14.500 --> 00:28:17.440
And the first three minute
overview that we showed you

00:28:17.440 --> 00:28:19.630
was season seven from that.

00:28:19.630 --> 00:28:23.140
And then the interesting thing
about this was that, over this

00:28:23.140 --> 00:28:26.150
period of time, we chose to
go with public television,

00:28:26.150 --> 00:28:28.790
because we could have a
mission-based approach, the

00:28:28.790 --> 00:28:30.610
creative control.

00:28:30.610 --> 00:28:32.750
But the interesting part was
that by doing that, public

00:28:32.750 --> 00:28:35.250
television also allows you to
maintain the rights to all of

00:28:35.250 --> 00:28:36.550
your content.

00:28:36.550 --> 00:28:38.650
If we would have gone with like
an MTV or something, it

00:28:38.650 --> 00:28:40.780
would have been gobbled
up by Viacom.

00:28:40.780 --> 00:28:42.420
And we would have had
a salary from them.

00:28:42.420 --> 00:28:46.550
But because it was public media,
we were able to then

00:28:46.550 --> 00:28:48.740
build an independent
organization around it and

00:28:48.740 --> 00:28:51.036
have some longevity.

00:28:51.036 --> 00:28:52.350
So can you show the
content archive.

00:28:52.350 --> 00:28:52.780
NATHAN GEBHARD: Yeah.

00:28:52.780 --> 00:28:54.870
MIKE MARRINER: So, essentially,
now, 10 years

00:28:54.870 --> 00:28:57.910
later, after doing Roadtrip
Nation and mobilizing this

00:28:57.910 --> 00:29:00.810
movement of other student road
trips, not only were we

00:29:00.810 --> 00:29:03.310
mobilizing these experiences to
impact the student's lives

00:29:03.310 --> 00:29:05.130
who were participating and
creating this TV show and

00:29:05.130 --> 00:29:08.270
whatnot, we were also creating
this enormous digital content

00:29:08.270 --> 00:29:10.320
archive, which I don't think
we could have predicted the

00:29:10.320 --> 00:29:12.210
power of from the beginning.

00:29:12.210 --> 00:29:21.490
But, essentially, it's almost
like an ethnographic study.

00:29:21.490 --> 00:29:23.520
Someone called it that
the other day.

00:29:23.520 --> 00:29:26.835
But in terms of like, if you
did mobilize teams of road

00:29:26.835 --> 00:29:29.120
trippers, for 10 years, to go
across America and across the

00:29:29.120 --> 00:29:31.850
world and collect people's
personal stories, like a huge

00:29:31.850 --> 00:29:34.360
oral history project, and just
ask them a simple question,

00:29:34.360 --> 00:29:35.620
how did you figure out
what you wanted to

00:29:35.620 --> 00:29:36.200
do with your life?

00:29:36.200 --> 00:29:37.600
And what were the steps that
you've taken to get

00:29:37.600 --> 00:29:38.860
where you are today?

00:29:38.860 --> 00:29:40.590
And what are the insights
and lessons

00:29:40.590 --> 00:29:42.780
learned along that journey?

00:29:42.780 --> 00:29:45.250
Those are stories and insights
we've been collecting for the

00:29:45.250 --> 00:29:46.730
past 10 years.

00:29:46.730 --> 00:29:49.130
And that's what's really led us
into the new education work

00:29:49.130 --> 00:29:50.200
we're dealing.

00:29:50.200 --> 00:29:54.180
In 2008, we saw something really
interesting happening,

00:29:54.180 --> 00:29:57.440
outside a little town in
Pittsburgh called Mon valley.

00:29:57.440 --> 00:29:59.890
We'd been doing Roadtrip Nation,
as the college model,

00:29:59.890 --> 00:30:01.860
in the PBS series, for
about five years.

00:30:01.860 --> 00:30:04.410
And I think we're thinking
about, what's the next step

00:30:04.410 --> 00:30:05.420
for Roadtrip Nation?

00:30:05.420 --> 00:30:07.450
How can we spread this
impact further?

00:30:07.450 --> 00:30:09.740
We were mobilizing several
green RV trips a

00:30:09.740 --> 00:30:10.600
year, around the world.

00:30:10.600 --> 00:30:13.650
But was there another model that
could be accessible to

00:30:13.650 --> 00:30:15.940
more and more students,
especially students that are

00:30:15.940 --> 00:30:17.920
growing up in communities where
they don't have a lot of

00:30:17.920 --> 00:30:21.240
chances to explore or connect
with leaders and explore

00:30:21.240 --> 00:30:23.100
what's possible for
their own futures?

00:30:23.100 --> 00:30:25.820
And so, outside of Pittsburgh,
there was a little town called

00:30:25.820 --> 00:30:27.570
Mon Valley, a school
district there.

00:30:27.570 --> 00:30:30.370
And there was a lot of,
essentially, mining

00:30:30.370 --> 00:30:31.290
jobs in that area.

00:30:31.290 --> 00:30:33.020
But the mining industry
was drying up.

00:30:33.020 --> 00:30:35.640
And the district was looking
for a way to engage their

00:30:35.640 --> 00:30:37.550
students and show them that
there's a whole world of

00:30:37.550 --> 00:30:39.490
possibilities for
their future.

00:30:39.490 --> 00:30:41.730
In short, they were looking
for a project, a career

00:30:41.730 --> 00:30:44.170
exploration project based
learning activity.

00:30:44.170 --> 00:30:48.530
And our documentary series was
airing on prime time in WQED.

00:30:48.530 --> 00:30:50.330
And some of the leadership in
the school district there

00:30:50.330 --> 00:30:51.850
said, we've got an idea.

00:30:51.850 --> 00:30:54.540
Let's do a Roadtrip Nation
Western Pennsylvania.

00:30:54.540 --> 00:30:55.870
And let's localize it.

00:30:55.870 --> 00:30:57.870
And this is when things really
got interesting.

00:30:57.870 --> 00:31:02.430
Because it showed us that you
really don't need a green RV

00:31:02.430 --> 00:31:04.810
or a cross-country trip
to have the impact

00:31:04.810 --> 00:31:05.600
from Roadtrip Nation.

00:31:05.600 --> 00:31:08.320
When you really strip it away,
the impact was always about

00:31:08.320 --> 00:31:10.130
these conversations that were
happening on the road, the

00:31:10.130 --> 00:31:11.780
people that you meet.

00:31:11.780 --> 00:31:13.770
And so these students, in Mon
Valley, and their teachers,

00:31:13.770 --> 00:31:16.190
they created this ad hoc, duct
tape Roadtrip Nation

00:31:16.190 --> 00:31:17.170
curriculum.

00:31:17.170 --> 00:31:19.220
And the students were road
tripping around Western

00:31:19.220 --> 00:31:21.970
Pennsylvania and Mon Valley, in
their own cars, on school

00:31:21.970 --> 00:31:25.220
buses, just on day trips,
interviewing entrepreneurs,

00:31:25.220 --> 00:31:28.060
local restaurateurs, the
taqueria owner, the guy who

00:31:28.060 --> 00:31:31.350
started the movie store, local
small businesses, EMT

00:31:31.350 --> 00:31:32.630
technicians.

00:31:32.630 --> 00:31:36.730
And we had been somewhat
following this, but we were

00:31:36.730 --> 00:31:38.910
more involved in our TV show
and that kind of a thing.

00:31:38.910 --> 00:31:41.070
At the end of the year,
they flew us out.

00:31:41.070 --> 00:31:44.430
And we walked into this
conference area, hall, where

00:31:44.430 --> 00:31:47.420
there was hundreds of kids,
organized into teams of three,

00:31:47.420 --> 00:31:50.360
showing off their projects,
with poster boards and

00:31:50.360 --> 00:31:52.570
computers, with showing some of
the videos from their road

00:31:52.570 --> 00:31:54.320
trips and the people
they'd interviewed.

00:31:54.320 --> 00:31:56.260
And, at that moment, we knew
that we that we had stumbled

00:31:56.260 --> 00:31:59.800
upon what we thought could be
the ultimate incarnation of

00:31:59.800 --> 00:32:02.780
what the Roadtrip Nation
movement could be, which was

00:32:02.780 --> 00:32:05.610
not only having people watch
the experiences of other

00:32:05.610 --> 00:32:08.900
students, who were lucky go in
the green RV, but to actually

00:32:08.900 --> 00:32:11.060
create the experience
themselves.

00:32:11.060 --> 00:32:14.220
So in 2008, we launched
roadtripnation.org, as a

00:32:14.220 --> 00:32:17.530
501(c)3 organization, that
creates curriculum and tools

00:32:17.530 --> 00:32:21.670
and resources for teachers,
especially in low income

00:32:21.670 --> 00:32:25.340
communities, to bring this
Roadtrip Nation experience to

00:32:25.340 --> 00:32:26.810
their students.

00:32:26.810 --> 00:32:28.600
So we're going to walk you
through a little bit of that

00:32:28.600 --> 00:32:28.980
curriculum.

00:32:28.980 --> 00:32:31.590
Before he keep going, is there
any quick questions on the

00:32:31.590 --> 00:32:34.290
history of Roadtrip Nation or
how we got here, before we

00:32:34.290 --> 00:32:36.690
dive into the education piece?

00:32:36.690 --> 00:32:39.430
NATHAN GEBHARD: The real
exciting part.

00:32:39.430 --> 00:32:41.820
AUDIENCE: You've become experts
on this topic, right?

00:32:41.820 --> 00:32:43.816
Because you've had a movie, you
got a book, so people come

00:32:43.816 --> 00:32:45.812
up to you and say, so what
should I do with my life?

00:32:45.812 --> 00:32:47.310
You get this question.

00:32:47.310 --> 00:32:49.040
So besides telling them that
they should be a product

00:32:49.040 --> 00:32:51.620
manager at Google, what
else do you tell them?

00:32:51.620 --> 00:32:54.560
MIKE MARRINER: Be a product
manager at Google.

00:32:54.560 --> 00:32:56.040
I think you guys hit
the jackpot.

00:32:56.040 --> 00:32:57.970
NATHAN GEBHARD: I think we
really try not to be the

00:32:57.970 --> 00:32:59.120
experts in anything.

00:32:59.120 --> 00:33:01.860
I think, for us, it wasn't
about people

00:33:01.860 --> 00:33:03.100
telling us what to do.

00:33:03.100 --> 00:33:05.920
I mean, I think everybody
can relate to that.

00:33:05.920 --> 00:33:09.040
To discover your own road, to
make it for yourself, that

00:33:09.040 --> 00:33:10.990
matters so much more than
somebody coming down and

00:33:10.990 --> 00:33:12.770
saying, you know, you
look like you'd

00:33:12.770 --> 00:33:14.240
make a great plumber.

00:33:14.240 --> 00:33:16.790
And so for us, our whole
experience is

00:33:16.790 --> 00:33:18.110
about sharing stories.

00:33:18.110 --> 00:33:21.520
And so it's not for us to become
the experts on career

00:33:21.520 --> 00:33:22.240
exploration.

00:33:22.240 --> 00:33:25.360
It's for us to present the
avenue and the opportunity to

00:33:25.360 --> 00:33:28.260
explore, for the individual, and
for that person to define

00:33:28.260 --> 00:33:29.890
their own road.

00:33:29.890 --> 00:33:33.205
So experts of none, maybe.

00:33:33.205 --> 00:33:36.460
AUDIENCE: Did you make the cold
calls before the trip, or

00:33:36.460 --> 00:33:38.960
you were calling people
along the trip?

00:33:38.960 --> 00:33:40.610
BRIAN MCALLISTER: Yeah, that's
a really good question.

00:33:40.610 --> 00:33:41.820
We made all the cold calls.

00:33:41.820 --> 00:33:44.460
And we actually booked all the
interviews before we left.

00:33:44.460 --> 00:33:45.280
AUDIENCE: How many?

00:33:45.280 --> 00:33:45.920
How many were there?

00:33:45.920 --> 00:33:47.510
BRIAN MCALLISTER: 84
interviews total.

00:33:47.510 --> 00:33:48.820
So we had a lot of intention.

00:33:48.820 --> 00:33:53.120
It wasn't like we were nomads
just kind going with the wind,

00:33:53.120 --> 00:33:54.660
and wherever we end
up, we end up.

00:33:54.660 --> 00:33:55.780
We had a lot of intention.

00:33:55.780 --> 00:33:57.520
I think it was a lot to just
prove to our parents that we

00:33:57.520 --> 00:33:59.315
had a project happening.

00:33:59.315 --> 00:34:01.440
As you guys can remember, at
that age, when people are--

00:34:01.440 --> 00:34:02.050
your parents.

00:34:02.050 --> 00:34:04.390
And we had a lot of pressure
from like, what are you guys

00:34:04.390 --> 00:34:05.000
going to do?

00:34:05.000 --> 00:34:07.660
And we really felt that we
wanted to have that intention

00:34:07.660 --> 00:34:08.739
lined upfront.

00:34:08.739 --> 00:34:10.989
And once we start booking
interviews, we really needed

00:34:10.989 --> 00:34:12.630
to schedule all that
out, right?

00:34:12.630 --> 00:34:15.710
So once we landed an interview
with Justice Sandra Day

00:34:15.710 --> 00:34:18.520
O'Connor, then we wanted to
interview some other folks.

00:34:18.520 --> 00:34:20.489
You really started to build
out the itinerary.

00:34:20.489 --> 00:34:22.070
And that actually really
built a lot of

00:34:22.070 --> 00:34:23.370
momentum for our project.

00:34:23.370 --> 00:34:26.980
AUDIENCE: How did you screen
out the 84 people?

00:34:26.980 --> 00:34:28.320
BRIAN MCALLISTER: Yeah, it's
kind of a self-selecting

00:34:28.320 --> 00:34:30.370
prophecy, almost.

00:34:30.370 --> 00:34:31.330
A lot of people said, no.

00:34:31.330 --> 00:34:32.590
We got rejected a lot.

00:34:32.590 --> 00:34:34.880
And the people that we accepted
was really based on,

00:34:34.880 --> 00:34:36.449
they remembered a time,
in their life, that

00:34:36.449 --> 00:34:37.389
they were like us.

00:34:37.389 --> 00:34:38.810
And so it's almost
like giving back.

00:34:38.810 --> 00:34:40.650
And I think that was one of the
biggest things, why people

00:34:40.650 --> 00:34:44.110
said, well, how do a couple
scrappy kids, out of college,

00:34:44.110 --> 00:34:46.650
book some of these interviews
with Michael Dell or Howard

00:34:46.650 --> 00:34:49.265
Schultz, the chairman of
Starbucks, or the hair stylist

00:34:49.265 --> 00:34:50.989
to Madonna and Lenny Kravitz?

00:34:50.989 --> 00:34:52.989
Honestly, they remember the time
in their lives that they

00:34:52.989 --> 00:34:53.969
could have used some
of the advice that

00:34:53.969 --> 00:34:55.060
they were giving us.

00:34:55.060 --> 00:34:56.370
They identified with us.

00:34:56.370 --> 00:35:00.380
And I think, once they saw us,
that age and that turmoil or

00:35:00.380 --> 00:35:03.410
that ambiguity creeped back in,
saying, wow, I wish I had

00:35:03.410 --> 00:35:05.900
someone that would have put
some advice on my table.

00:35:05.900 --> 00:35:08.840
And so they really identified
with the age and our

00:35:08.840 --> 00:35:10.825
situations that we were
going through.

00:35:10.825 --> 00:35:12.930
MIKE MARRINER: And we've seen
that with the students today,

00:35:12.930 --> 00:35:13.960
who are going through
the curriculum.

00:35:13.960 --> 00:35:16.766
So over the last 3 years, over
100,000 students have gone

00:35:16.766 --> 00:35:18.440
through the Roadtrip Nation
Experience curriculum, on a

00:35:18.440 --> 00:35:19.470
high school level.

00:35:19.470 --> 00:35:21.120
And it's the same thing.

00:35:21.120 --> 00:35:24.530
Our first pilot ever, for the
curriculum, was in Fresno, in

00:35:24.530 --> 00:35:27.200
a corner of Fresno called Orosi,
California, southeast

00:35:27.200 --> 00:35:28.170
Fresno County.

00:35:28.170 --> 00:35:30.395
And a lot of the students there
and the teachers and the

00:35:30.395 --> 00:35:32.170
school district at first was
like, who are they going to

00:35:32.170 --> 00:35:33.430
interview in Orosi,
there's no one.

00:35:33.430 --> 00:35:35.070
There's no Michael Dell
here or whatever.

00:35:35.070 --> 00:35:37.050
But what we realize is that
their are leaders in

00:35:37.050 --> 00:35:37.710
everyone's community.

00:35:37.710 --> 00:35:40.600
When you localize it, those
conversations become even more

00:35:40.600 --> 00:35:44.260
relevant and more impactful,
because there's a gap in

00:35:44.260 --> 00:35:47.120
social capital we've seen a
lot of communities, where

00:35:47.120 --> 00:35:50.450
students, from a certain part of
Orosi, may not have access

00:35:50.450 --> 00:35:54.990
to interviewing even EMT
technicians or local lawyers

00:35:54.990 --> 00:35:56.830
or local government officials.

00:35:56.830 --> 00:35:58.800
One team, from Fresno,
interviewed

00:35:58.800 --> 00:35:59.750
the mayor of Fresno.

00:35:59.750 --> 00:36:01.780
And to them, the mayor of Fresno
was like Barack Obama.

00:36:01.780 --> 00:36:04.060
That was like the biggest
deal ever.

00:36:04.060 --> 00:36:07.350
And one of the most impactful
interviews we've ever seen was

00:36:07.350 --> 00:36:08.700
in our first pilot.

00:36:08.700 --> 00:36:10.650
Some of the students there
interviewed a gang violence

00:36:10.650 --> 00:36:14.150
activist, in southeast Fresno
county, who was in one of the

00:36:14.150 --> 00:36:18.100
earliest Central California
gangs, was put in prison years

00:36:18.100 --> 00:36:20.590
when he was like 19 years old,
got out on early parole,

00:36:20.590 --> 00:36:23.990
because he worked off
some of his time.

00:36:23.990 --> 00:36:26.030
And now he's giving back
to his community.

00:36:26.030 --> 00:36:28.640
But to him, to those students,
that issue of gang violence is

00:36:28.640 --> 00:36:31.820
so central, in the California
Central Valley, that that was

00:36:31.820 --> 00:36:36.500
their Michael Dell and to have
them localize that experience.

00:36:36.500 --> 00:36:38.320
And so what we've seen is that
now the students are doing the

00:36:38.320 --> 00:36:39.130
cold calling.

00:36:39.130 --> 00:36:41.020
And that's part of
the curriculum.

00:36:41.020 --> 00:36:43.320
And so, actually, why don't we
just jump into showing a

00:36:43.320 --> 00:36:44.490
little except of
the curriculum.

00:36:44.490 --> 00:36:46.940
But this was one of the big
humps we had to get through

00:36:46.940 --> 00:36:49.860
from Roadtrip Nation, which
was how do you scale the

00:36:49.860 --> 00:36:50.920
impact of this experience?

00:36:50.920 --> 00:36:54.610
We know that providing a
transformative experience by

00:36:54.610 --> 00:36:56.470
helping students to get outside
of their comfort zone,

00:36:56.470 --> 00:36:59.940
connecting with leaders is a
huge way to help students

00:36:59.940 --> 00:37:01.770
figure out what they want
to do with their lives.

00:37:01.770 --> 00:37:04.910
But being in the green RVs
is obviously limiting.

00:37:04.910 --> 00:37:07.720
And so what we did was-- if you
can click on the lessons

00:37:07.720 --> 00:37:10.280
and projects, the table
of contents.

00:37:10.280 --> 00:37:13.550
So this is essentially
roadtripnation.org.

00:37:13.550 --> 00:37:16.460
There's a roadtripnation.com,
which is our public television

00:37:16.460 --> 00:37:18.680
focused site and college
programs and

00:37:18.680 --> 00:37:20.000
student facing site.

00:37:20.000 --> 00:37:22.440
Roadtripnation.org is the
educational resources that

00:37:22.440 --> 00:37:24.910
school districts bring into
the classroom as a project

00:37:24.910 --> 00:37:26.060
based learning curriculum.

00:37:26.060 --> 00:37:28.940
It's been aligned to the
Educational Standards for

00:37:28.940 --> 00:37:30.300
English Language Arts.

00:37:30.300 --> 00:37:32.690
So it's like official on the
back end and funded by the

00:37:32.690 --> 00:37:34.330
California Department of
Education and the Hewlett

00:37:34.330 --> 00:37:34.970
Foundation.

00:37:34.970 --> 00:37:38.550
But on the front end, it feels
student based and exactly like

00:37:38.550 --> 00:37:40.660
you would feel if you're living
in the motor home for

00:37:40.660 --> 00:37:41.690
three months.

00:37:41.690 --> 00:37:44.450
So it's kind of a window into
what we hope is the future of

00:37:44.450 --> 00:37:47.360
education, which is more for
students, by students

00:37:47.360 --> 00:37:50.290
curriculum and programming
that really empowers and

00:37:50.290 --> 00:37:52.490
galvanizes students on the front
end, rather than just

00:37:52.490 --> 00:37:54.420
like hitting them with standards
and tests and

00:37:54.420 --> 00:37:57.550
rubrics on the back end,
focusing more upstream on the

00:37:57.550 --> 00:38:01.160
more self-efficacy, student
agency side of the equation,

00:38:01.160 --> 00:38:02.550
that will then help
them to engage.

00:38:02.550 --> 00:38:04.720
And then you start to see some
of those outcomes downstream,

00:38:04.720 --> 00:38:06.770
rather focusing it the
other way around.

00:38:06.770 --> 00:38:09.440
So essentially, the curriculum
is a three part curriculum.

00:38:09.440 --> 00:38:11.160
Part one is called exposure.

00:38:11.160 --> 00:38:12.800
Part two is called
self-construction.

00:38:12.800 --> 00:38:14.850
And part three is the
Roadtrip project.

00:38:14.850 --> 00:38:17.340
Part three is the component
where it's the big culminating

00:38:17.340 --> 00:38:19.380
piece of actually going out,
in their communities, and

00:38:19.380 --> 00:38:21.210
building these projects.

00:38:21.210 --> 00:38:23.040
But we knew, with a lot of the
populations that we were

00:38:23.040 --> 00:38:25.870
serving, having them to
basically build a Roadtrip is

00:38:25.870 --> 00:38:27.420
kind of like, sure, right.

00:38:27.420 --> 00:38:29.730
I'm going to go cold call the
mayor of my local town or like

00:38:29.730 --> 00:38:30.680
an EMT technician.

00:38:30.680 --> 00:38:33.340
We realized we needed to
have some exploratory

00:38:33.340 --> 00:38:34.660
experience up front.

00:38:34.660 --> 00:38:37.290
So for part one, what we did
was we had our staff go

00:38:37.290 --> 00:38:40.310
through the entire interview
archive, of 1,100 interviews

00:38:40.310 --> 00:38:42.410
over the last 10 years,
and start to take that

00:38:42.410 --> 00:38:45.080
ethnographic approach of,
essentially, boiling down the

00:38:45.080 --> 00:38:47.660
common themes and insights of
how these leaders have figured

00:38:47.660 --> 00:38:49.500
out what they wanted to
do with their lives.

00:38:49.500 --> 00:38:51.380
We then took those themes and
boiled them down to what we

00:38:51.380 --> 00:38:54.180
call the seven core axles of
Roadtrip Nation, which are

00:38:54.180 --> 00:38:56.900
these real life insights, in
terms of how people have

00:38:56.900 --> 00:38:58.340
figured out what they wanted
t do with their life.

00:38:58.340 --> 00:39:05.570
So if you didn't grow up with
Howard Schultz as your dad or

00:39:05.570 --> 00:39:07.500
someone who had these incredible
insights, this is a

00:39:07.500 --> 00:39:09.210
way to boil that down.

00:39:12.580 --> 00:39:14.570
And then each lesson--

00:39:14.570 --> 00:39:15.630
like making it work,
we're going to

00:39:15.630 --> 00:39:16.790
play here in a second--

00:39:16.790 --> 00:39:19.700
is essentially boiled down into
these topical lessons,

00:39:19.700 --> 00:39:21.190
from the archive, along
this theme.

00:39:21.190 --> 00:39:23.100
So we're going to play one
sample lesson here, which is

00:39:23.100 --> 00:39:25.480
making it work, which we heard
time and time again.

00:39:25.480 --> 00:39:28.200
This is a perfect commonality.

00:39:28.200 --> 00:39:30.690
Finding your road in life
is not always easy.

00:39:30.690 --> 00:39:32.420
It's not like you just
stick it, find your

00:39:32.420 --> 00:39:34.490
dream, and make it happen.

00:39:34.490 --> 00:39:38.100
Along the way, there are
lots of potholes.

