And I think some of it was
probably driven from the

00:53:48.800 --> 00:53:49.560
economic side.

00:53:49.560 --> 00:53:52.790
But I think a lot of this
younger generation we're

00:53:52.790 --> 00:53:54.350
working with, they want to be
a part of something that was

00:53:54.350 --> 00:53:56.280
going last the test of time.

00:53:56.280 --> 00:53:58.190
So I think mission-driven is
starting to become a pretty

00:53:58.190 --> 00:53:59.810
big theme, as you guys know.

00:53:59.810 --> 00:54:01.980
MIKE MARRINER: And that last
theme of making it work, we've

00:54:01.980 --> 00:54:04.930
seen that be more pervasive
as well.

00:54:04.930 --> 00:54:07.070
You can follow what it is you're
really passionate about

00:54:07.070 --> 00:54:07.920
and define your own road.

00:54:07.920 --> 00:54:09.340
But you've got to find a
way to make it work.

00:54:09.340 --> 00:54:11.050
That's why that whole theme in
the curriculum was called,

00:54:11.050 --> 00:54:11.780
making it work.

00:54:11.780 --> 00:54:13.690
Because, essentially, you might
see someone who's the

00:54:13.690 --> 00:54:18.660
director of "Saturday Night
Live," but what you also need

00:54:18.660 --> 00:54:21.290
to hear is that she worked at
the Gap, for two years, during

00:54:21.290 --> 00:54:22.890
the holidays, so she
could pay her rent.

00:54:22.890 --> 00:54:23.850
Because she was getting
paid next to

00:54:23.850 --> 00:54:25.840
nothing doing her thing.

00:54:25.840 --> 00:54:29.080
And I'm sure even guys, like the
roots of Google, you see

00:54:29.080 --> 00:54:29.940
this huge thing today.

00:54:29.940 --> 00:54:31.790
But I'm sure, in the early
days, there was a lot of

00:54:31.790 --> 00:54:33.650
making it work that had to
happen, whether it was

00:54:33.650 --> 00:54:36.210
starting it out of a garage or
whatever, not being in this

00:54:36.210 --> 00:54:39.110
big, fancy office building.

00:54:39.110 --> 00:54:41.780
In America, we're so success
obsessed, in our culture, we

00:54:41.780 --> 00:54:43.730
kind of forget those parts
of the story, like

00:54:43.730 --> 00:54:45.180
the groveling periods.

00:54:45.180 --> 00:54:47.660
And I think that we've really
tried to celebrate that with

00:54:47.660 --> 00:54:49.500
Roadtrip Nation, where we're
looking back on these people

00:54:49.500 --> 00:54:52.680
stories as like, these are the
grinding times, when, yes,

00:54:52.680 --> 00:54:55.210
they may have taken a
really tough path.

00:54:55.210 --> 00:54:57.920
But how do we inspire and
empower the next generation of

00:54:57.920 --> 00:54:59.360
leaders, too?

00:54:59.360 --> 00:55:02.170
Who's going to be the next
person that cures cancer?

00:55:02.170 --> 00:55:05.180
What if there's a kid out there
who has a real genius

00:55:05.180 --> 00:55:07.750
instinct for science, but who
never really connected with

00:55:07.750 --> 00:55:10.580
that interest, because, A, there
was too much noise and

00:55:10.580 --> 00:55:13.300
pressure around them to not go
away to college, to stay home

00:55:13.300 --> 00:55:15.830
and be with family,
or, B, that it's

00:55:15.830 --> 00:55:16.850
going to be too hard.

00:55:16.850 --> 00:55:18.440
I don't want to make it work.

00:55:18.440 --> 00:55:19.120
Getting my Ph.D.?

00:55:19.120 --> 00:55:19.750
No freaking way.

00:55:19.750 --> 00:55:21.810
I'm going to go do something
much easier.

00:55:21.810 --> 00:55:24.220
So what we're trying
to is decipher all

00:55:24.220 --> 00:55:25.130
these stories down.

00:55:25.130 --> 00:55:28.890
And I think that, as culture
changes, there is some kind of

00:55:28.890 --> 00:55:29.830
tonality shifts.

00:55:29.830 --> 00:55:32.770
But I think, per Nate's point, a
lot of the core ethos remain

00:55:32.770 --> 00:55:34.690
pretty consistent.

00:55:34.690 --> 00:55:36.400
AUDIENCE: Have you ever thought
to expand this program

00:55:36.400 --> 00:55:37.650
internationally?

00:55:39.840 --> 00:55:40.530
MIKE MARRINER: Yes.

00:55:40.530 --> 00:55:42.910
We have done a few international
Roadtrips.

00:55:42.910 --> 00:55:45.480
We actually started to tone
it back a little bit, only

00:55:45.480 --> 00:55:47.660
because we realized that
America is so big.

00:55:47.660 --> 00:55:48.860
And now that we've really
gotten into the

00:55:48.860 --> 00:55:49.750
heavy lifting work.

00:55:49.750 --> 00:55:52.570
I mean, talk about hard work,
like education, that is really

00:55:52.570 --> 00:55:55.840
hard, complicated,
incredible work.

00:55:55.840 --> 00:55:59.840
And so when we started to see
how, over the last 3 years,

00:55:59.840 --> 00:56:01.150
we've expanded to 22 states.

00:56:01.150 --> 00:56:02.700
And that has taken
all of our focus.

00:56:02.700 --> 00:56:05.400
So Roadtrip Nation, it's much
bigger than just Nate,

00:56:05.400 --> 00:56:06.150
Brian, and I now.

00:56:06.150 --> 00:56:07.220
We have 40 employees.

00:56:07.220 --> 00:56:09.600
We have an office based down
in Southern California, in

00:56:09.600 --> 00:56:11.250
Costa Mesa, right between
LA and San.

00:56:11.250 --> 00:56:14.710
Diego and we have 40, totally
dedicated, passionate

00:56:14.710 --> 00:56:16.930
individual who are building
this, editing the footage,

00:56:16.930 --> 00:56:20.070
implementing the curriculum,
working with the schools,

00:56:20.070 --> 00:56:21.880
researching the data,
all of that.

00:56:21.880 --> 00:56:26.250
And so I think we've seen the
need to focus that effort,

00:56:26.250 --> 00:56:27.390
domestically, for now.

00:56:27.390 --> 00:56:30.870
But we do, ultimately, have a
vision of going to countries

00:56:30.870 --> 00:56:32.880
around the world that really,
obviously, where their youth

00:56:32.880 --> 00:56:35.100
are in high need of figuring
out what their

00:56:35.100 --> 00:56:37.140
futures are as well.

00:56:37.140 --> 00:56:38.870
AUDIENCE: To what degree have
you found that it's not just

00:56:38.870 --> 00:56:42.310
adversity that people are
overcoming but also a sense of

00:56:42.310 --> 00:56:45.070
diversity in their lives, or in
their work experience and

00:56:45.070 --> 00:56:47.330
stuff like that, that's really
helped fuel them or push them

00:56:47.330 --> 00:56:48.580
onto their ultimate careers?

00:56:51.810 --> 00:56:52.320
NATHAN GEBHARD: Diversity?

00:56:52.320 --> 00:56:53.630
In what sense do you mean?

00:56:53.630 --> 00:56:56.430
AUDIENCE: Diversity and like
difference in things they've

00:56:56.430 --> 00:56:58.590
done or experiences that
they've had and stuff.

00:56:58.590 --> 00:57:01.670
Because I think we hear that
constant plea of follow your

00:57:01.670 --> 00:57:02.980
passion and that
kind of thing.

00:57:02.980 --> 00:57:05.100
But part of it is, sometimes,
people maybe--

00:57:05.100 --> 00:57:07.610
it's not like they don't have
passions or particular

00:57:07.610 --> 00:57:09.710
passions, but they don't really
know what their passion

00:57:09.710 --> 00:57:11.930
is or where they would
find that.

00:57:11.930 --> 00:57:16.390
So in experiencing a diverse
life or diverse jobs or a

00:57:16.390 --> 00:57:18.770
diverse career paths and that
kind of thing can sometimes

00:57:18.770 --> 00:57:22.370
lead you then to, eventually,
what it is

00:57:22.370 --> 00:57:24.620
that you really love.

00:57:24.620 --> 00:57:27.870
NATHAN GEBHARD: I think I would
say that diversity, that

00:57:27.870 --> 00:57:32.860
ability and that comfort to kind
of just be OK wandering

00:57:32.860 --> 00:57:37.025
is something that an
instructor or a

00:57:37.025 --> 00:57:39.730
counselor or a parent--

00:57:39.730 --> 00:57:42.020
it's hard advice to
give to somebody.

00:57:42.020 --> 00:57:44.630
But I think, as we've
interviewed so many people,

00:57:44.630 --> 00:57:46.370
that's the reality
of their life.

00:57:46.370 --> 00:57:52.200
I mean I think that sense of
just bumping into things is a

00:57:52.200 --> 00:57:53.410
really important part.

00:57:53.410 --> 00:57:56.210
And I think what we've seen is
that the people that are

00:57:56.210 --> 00:57:59.110
comfortable following their own
compass and then having

00:57:59.110 --> 00:58:02.470
that diversity of experience,
those are the ones that start

00:58:02.470 --> 00:58:05.380
on one thing and then realize,
oh, well, there's something

00:58:05.380 --> 00:58:06.690
about this that's interesting.

00:58:06.690 --> 00:58:07.880
And there's something
about this.

00:58:07.880 --> 00:58:10.400
And if I put them together,
I'll get here.

00:58:10.400 --> 00:58:12.900
But those that take that linear
path often miss those

00:58:12.900 --> 00:58:13.840
other opportunities.

00:58:13.840 --> 00:58:17.150
So I think some of the most
interesting people have been

00:58:17.150 --> 00:58:19.580
comfortable wandering
and changing careers

00:58:19.580 --> 00:58:20.430
and starting over.

00:58:20.430 --> 00:58:22.930
And there's countless examples
of people that we've had that

00:58:22.930 --> 00:58:25.870
have had that exact
experience.

00:58:25.870 --> 00:58:28.570
AUDIENCE: I know you primarily
targeted schoolchildren and

00:58:28.570 --> 00:58:29.980
people who were starting up.

00:58:29.980 --> 00:58:32.840
What's your experience with
people who are in a midlife

00:58:32.840 --> 00:58:36.110
crisis or who need to figure
out the next thing?

00:58:36.110 --> 00:58:38.970
They had like a mindless,
corporate job for majority of

00:58:38.970 --> 00:58:40.880
their lives.

00:58:40.880 --> 00:58:42.380
Not Google, by the way.

00:58:42.380 --> 00:58:43.840
[LAUGHTER]

00:58:43.840 --> 00:58:47.440
So what's your experience
been?

00:58:47.440 --> 00:58:48.990
MIKE MARRINER: Our mission,
very intentionally, is to

00:58:48.990 --> 00:58:51.520
empower people to define their
own roads in life.

00:58:51.520 --> 00:58:53.400
We've only been really focusing
on students, because

00:58:53.400 --> 00:58:55.410
they're so vulnerable at that
age, especially in certain

00:58:55.410 --> 00:58:57.560
geographical locations
around America.

00:58:57.560 --> 00:59:00.540
If you don't focus on some
demographics of students, like

00:59:00.540 --> 00:59:03.170
the alternate thing is a student
that drops out of high

00:59:03.170 --> 00:59:06.080
school is eight times as likely
to be more incarcerated

00:59:06.080 --> 00:59:09.120
or living on welfare or to have
kids that are also on

00:59:09.120 --> 00:59:11.870
welfare and be incarcerated.

00:59:11.870 --> 00:59:15.650
But we hear, all the time,
because of the PBS series, the

00:59:15.650 --> 00:59:17.260
demographic is a little
bit older.

00:59:17.260 --> 00:59:19.460
And we hear, all the time, that
the message is timeless.

00:59:19.460 --> 00:59:21.560
The messages is you don't just
define your own road in life

00:59:21.560 --> 00:59:24.010
when you're 18 years old, and
then you like stick it, great,

00:59:24.010 --> 00:59:26.110
no big deal.

00:59:26.110 --> 00:59:27.600
Defining your own road
in life happens

00:59:27.600 --> 00:59:28.600
throughout your entire life.

00:59:28.600 --> 00:59:32.020
And so especially when you get
in your 30s, 40s, 50s and you

00:59:32.020 --> 00:59:34.760
have this wealth of experience,
just kind of being

00:59:34.760 --> 00:59:38.300
open and pliable and taking a
lot of these same ethos and

00:59:38.300 --> 00:59:39.840
themes and applying them
to your own life.

00:59:39.840 --> 00:59:42.200
Like Nate was saying, mashing
it up, having more

00:59:42.200 --> 00:59:45.280
experiences, be comfortable
with wandering.

00:59:45.280 --> 00:59:49.590
I think that we absolutely
see as a lifelong piece.

00:59:49.590 --> 00:59:51.110
NATHAN GEBHARD: I think one
story that comes to mind is

00:59:51.110 --> 00:59:52.780
the founder of Sam Adams.

00:59:52.780 --> 00:59:54.230
He was a consultant.

00:59:54.230 --> 00:59:56.340
And I think he was at Bain
Capital, I think.

00:59:56.340 --> 00:59:57.360
MIKE MARRINER: Boston
Consulting Group.

00:59:57.360 --> 00:59:59.450
NATHAN GEBHARD: Boston
Consulting Group.

00:59:59.450 --> 01:00:02.270
And here he was, going
through the machine.

01:00:02.270 --> 01:00:03.370
He was part of that machine.

01:00:03.370 --> 01:00:06.360
And there are consultants that
absolutely love what they do.

01:00:06.360 --> 01:00:08.240
But he just wasn't
one of them.

01:00:08.240 --> 01:00:11.180
And when the Roadtrippers
were asking him like,

01:00:11.180 --> 01:00:12.150
what about that risk?

01:00:12.150 --> 01:00:13.970
You leave this really high
paying job, and you're going

01:00:13.970 --> 01:00:16.310
to go brew beer in your
mom's kitchen?

01:00:16.310 --> 01:00:18.620
And you watched him pause
for a while and

01:00:18.620 --> 01:00:20.350
really think about it.

01:00:20.350 --> 01:00:21.295
And I loved his reaction.

01:00:21.295 --> 01:00:23.840
And his reaction was, the bigger
risk would have been

01:00:23.840 --> 01:00:27.110
staying and doing something that
I didn't love then taking

01:00:27.110 --> 01:00:30.600
this risk in brewing beer
in my mom's kitchen.

01:00:30.600 --> 01:00:35.250
And I think that it's the
clarity and the confidence

01:00:35.250 --> 01:00:37.090
that need to come together
in those moments.

01:00:37.090 --> 01:00:40.740
And so the exposure we have is
that, while it's young people

01:00:40.740 --> 01:00:42.270
roadtripping, we're talking
to people that

01:00:42.270 --> 01:00:43.110
have figured it out.

01:00:43.110 --> 01:00:44.740
So we're getting it
on both ends.

01:00:44.740 --> 01:00:47.980
But that's an example
that comes to mind.

01:00:47.980 --> 01:00:48.890
We can chill, too.

01:00:48.890 --> 01:00:51.290
AUDIENCE: Why, I was going to
say, to close, what is the

01:00:51.290 --> 01:00:55.210
number one tip you have for
driving an RV across your 10

01:00:55.210 --> 01:00:56.290
years of experience?

01:00:56.290 --> 01:00:57.910
MIKE MARRINER: RV driving
is a team sport.

01:00:57.910 --> 01:01:01.180
That was our whole thing.

01:01:01.180 --> 01:01:03.630
I think that our first road trip
prepared us for building

01:01:03.630 --> 01:01:04.770
a business together.

01:01:04.770 --> 01:01:07.550
Because if you can get a motor
home, especially a 30 year old

01:01:07.550 --> 01:01:09.700
motor home, around the
country in one piece.

01:01:09.700 --> 01:01:13.720
And the same thing, like when
you're driving down the road,

01:01:13.720 --> 01:01:15.230
blind spot is an
understatement.

01:01:15.230 --> 01:01:17.770
I mean you really can't see when
you're changing lanes.

01:01:17.770 --> 01:01:20.520
So if you're going to change
lanes, it's like, I'm going to

01:01:20.520 --> 01:01:21.160
change lanes.

01:01:21.160 --> 01:01:24.260
So someone's out the window,
please, don't.

01:01:24.260 --> 01:01:26.490
I'm coming in.

01:01:26.490 --> 01:01:27.640
NATHAN GEBHARD: The oddest thing
is there's a rearview

01:01:27.640 --> 01:01:28.740
mirror in an RV.

01:01:28.740 --> 01:01:29.610
But you can't.

01:01:29.610 --> 01:01:30.870
There's no.

01:01:30.870 --> 01:01:32.290
You only look at the person
sitting on the

01:01:32.290 --> 01:01:34.180
couch behind you.

01:01:34.180 --> 01:01:36.500
BRIAN MCALLISTER: I would
say, don't wait

01:01:36.500 --> 01:01:38.680
until you master it.

01:01:38.680 --> 01:01:39.890
It's a work in progress.

01:01:39.890 --> 01:01:41.170
And that might be
a deep metaphor.

01:01:41.170 --> 01:01:43.830
But you got to hit the road,
sooner or later.

01:01:43.830 --> 01:01:48.200
And I would say, don't wait
until you've got it all

01:01:48.200 --> 01:01:48.590
figured out.

01:01:48.590 --> 01:01:50.790
Because, when you get to Boston,
and there's no grids

01:01:50.790 --> 01:01:52.350
there, you're screwed.

01:01:52.350 --> 01:01:55.110
So just train as you go.

01:01:55.110 --> 01:01:57.280
NATHAN GEBHARD: I would say be
comfortable getting lost.

01:01:57.280 --> 01:01:59.560
I think that's something that
actually I have a complaint

01:01:59.560 --> 01:02:02.140
about with the GPS is that
you don't get lost.

01:02:02.140 --> 01:02:04.850
And the number of times that we
had meaningful experiences

01:02:04.850 --> 01:02:07.040
when we just got lost.

01:02:07.040 --> 01:02:09.360
We've lost those lost moments.

01:02:09.360 --> 01:02:13.060
And so I think, in life or in
driving, get lost every once

01:02:13.060 --> 01:02:14.530
in a while.

01:02:14.530 --> 01:02:15.840
MALE SPEAKER: On that note,
thank you very much for

01:02:15.840 --> 01:02:16.600
speaking with us today.

01:02:16.600 --> 01:02:17.200
Amazing speech.

01:02:17.200 --> 01:02:22.405
[APPLAUSE]

